    <h1>Items vs. Variations</h1><div id="preamble">
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Items are made up of lots of information, e.g. categories, prices, manufacturers, descriptive texts and images. To help you manage items, this data is divided into three levels:</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>System settings</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Items</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Variations</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can think of <em>system settings</em> as information that applies to multiple items. For example, multiple items are sorted into the same category or manufactured by the same company. System settings are saved in plentymarkets one time and then applied to all of the corresponding items and variations.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can think of <em>items</em> as data containers. They always include one or more <em>variations</em>, i.e. one or more saleable versions of a product. For example, if you sell a t-shirt in small, medium and large, then all of these sizes together form the item. Each individual size is a variation of the item.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>In summary, the item structure is composed of three data levels:</p>
</div>
